{"cursor":"3202","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nIn materials science and metallurgy, 'toughness' is the ability of a material to\nabsorb energy and plastically deform without fracturing; [http://www.ndt-\ned.org/EducationResources/CommunityCollege/Materials/Mechanical/Toughness.htm\n\"Toughness\"], [http://www.ndt-ed.org/index_flash.htm NDT Education Resource\nCenter], Brian Larson, Editor, 2001-2011, The Collaboration for NDT Education,\nIowa State University Material toughness is defined as the amount of\nenergy per volume that a material can absorb before rupturing. It is also\ndefined as the resistance to fracture of a material when stressed.\n\nToughness requires a balance of strength and ductility.\n","linknr":150,"url":"Toughness","recorded":1362675738,"links":35,"instances":["physics","engineering","mechanics","mechanics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Continuum mechanics","Materials science","Physical quantities"],"headings":["Mathematical definition","Toughness tests","Unit of toughness","Toughness and strength","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/f/b/dfbf128f3781f48d6e3146e3cc779349.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/4/4/344f4ab091ca9d13f230aa8d9da4b435.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/d/2/0d25c4d1a7e8b9174f0918734e33fe00.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/d/4/9d43cb8bbcb702e9d5943de477f099e2.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["rupture","engineering"],["stress","physics"],["impact","mechanics"],["shock","mechanics"]],"members":["stress","rupture","shock","impact"],"related":["Materials_science","Metallurgy","Iowa_State_University","Energy","Rupture_(engineering)","Fracture","Stress_(physics)","Strength_o